Eighteen years ago after studying at the National School of Drama in New Delhi, Pankaj Tripathi (@pankajtripathi) made his way to Mumbai. Unlike many others who end up here, the actor remembers the exact day and date of his arrival in the city of opportunities. “It was October 16, 2004 when I reached Mumbai Central at 7.30 am by the Paschim Express,” he says with a smile, “It was a big decision of my life. I was newly married. I had come from zero. I didn’t know what would happen, when I would get an opportunity or how people would get to know that I am an actor. When you make a move towards uncertainty, then you remember that day well,” he adds.

By: Deepali Singh (@deepalisingh05)

#TheEstablished

A study published in 2003 in the International Journal of Information Management revealed that an average person typically takes 64 seconds to return to what they were doing before they were interrupted by an email. It also found that a typical employee checks their email once every five minutes. By that theory, that’s a whole minute lost every six minutes, simply switching. Is multitasking slowing you down? 

Our contributing writer Sneha Mankani spoke with psychiatrists and neurology experts to find out.

#multitasking #monotasking

“Growing up in north India, at least a dozen dishes were made for Holi every year. Amongst the savoury dishes, we would always have kanji vada (dal vada served with fermented black carrot drink) and mathi (an ajwain-flavoured fried snack),” says Delhi-based cuisine and nutrition consultant Sangeeta Khanna (@sangeetamkhanna). 

Should you wish to indulge in the bounty of delicacies typical to Holi with friends and family or even gift them to loved ones, there certainly is no dearth of options, contributing writer, Prachi Joshi. Perhaps the most symbolic of Holi treats, particularly in north India, is the crescent-shaped gujiya. Flaky pastry sheets made with refined flour and semolina are filled with a sweetened mixture of khoya or mawa along with dessicated coconut and dry fruits, deep-fried and often dipped in sugar syrup. From traditional options to nutty gujiyas stuffed with kalakand, jaggery ones from Bombay Sweet Shop. Tell us what’s on your plate this holi.

#holi #indianfood

Traditionally celebrity endorsements, magazine recommendations and word of mouth from friends and family were primary purchase influencers, but today, there’s a shift in the landscape. People just know more. They have access to more information, and the internet has been democratising it for years now. Anjan Sachar (@anjansachar)—a contributor at The Established—reached out to influencers, editors and brand founders to understand what’s working in the beauty influencing space—and what isn’t moving the needle.

#beauty #shopping

A giant leap for Apple iPhones in the Indian marketplace, is still a minuscule market share of the highly competitive world of the mobile phones. Market watchers are sitting up to register the fact that Apple (@apple) iPhones just recorded a massive 48 per cent growth for 2021. The Indian marketplace, though stays firm as an android nation,  as the cult brand adored by tech fiends, is still at a 4.4 per cent market for last year.

According to Gurugram-based market research firm CMR, Apple shipped a record 5.4 million iPhones to India in the entire year, and 2.2 million in the festive quarter (Q4) alone. CMR credits the growth spurt to Apple’s diversification of its supply chains through the pandemic. The iPhone model Indians were buying the most was the iPhone 12 followed by iPhone 11, SE (2020), iPhone 13 and iPhone 13 Pro Max models.

Apple has now started assembling its new flagship iPhone 13 in India, as the tech giant prepares to manufacture and assemble its top-of-the-line smartphones in the country. With such an impressive score card for the last year, what’s really expected to zoom sales further is the launch of the iPhone SE 2022 edition in the first half of 2022. Let the mobile phone wars continue!

📸: Apple (@apple) 

 #iPhones #Apple #mobilephones #technology #tech #technews

Do any indie music acts actually make money through digital service providers like Spotify? 42,100 musicians generated over $10,000 (Rs 7.5 lakh approximately) in royalties from the digital service provider in 2020. 

That's just 0.5 per cent of the eight million creators who distribute their content on the service. Also, $10,000 is less than minimum wage in the US. On the other hand, Spotify is not the only streaming platform from which artistes earn revenue. 

But it is the most dominant. Contributor Amit Gurbaxani (@AmitGurbaxani) checked in with a few of the country’s most successful independent musicians to find out how they define monetary success on music streaming services like Spotify (@spotifyindia) in today’s newsletter on #TheEstablished.

#indianmusic #musicians #spotifyindia #artists

For generations, marriage has been the ultimate marker of a woman’s success. But today, more Indian women are flipping the script—choosing financial freedom, investing in their own futures, and building chosen families on their own terms. 

“I have aspirations and want my own money to fall back on. I’m not waiting for a guy to buy me a new car,” says 31-year-old Tusharika Sharma.

From battling housing discrimination to sidestepping societal judgment, single women are crafting their own happily-ever-afters—no prince required. But is society ready to catch up?

By Karishma Kuenzang ( @kkuenzang )

Workaholism isn’t just about loving your job—it’s about knowing when to stop. In a world that glorifies hustle culture, where’s the line between passion and obsession? And when does chasing success start costing your relationship?

So, can workaholics have it all? Or is the very thing that fuels success also spelling failure for love?

Born and raised in Pune, Vaishnavi Walvekar (@vahe.ensemble) nurtured an appreciation for art and crafts from an early age. Deeply influenced by her mother’s artistic talent, Walekar was often surrounded by embroidery, wood, and metalworks. After completing an MFA in Industrial Design in San Francisco, she began to pick projects that were sustainable, driven by social innovation, or focused on craftsmanship. Now based in New Delhi, Walekar continues to explore the intersection of heritage and contemporary design through her brand, Vahe.

Vahe was born out of Walvekar’s fascination for India’s craft bazaars, where she saw immense potential in traditional materials beyond their conventional applications. A chance encounter with Kashmiri papier-mâché—a craft practised for centuries—became the foundation of her vision. Unlike modern paper crafts that often rely on chemical adhesives, papier-mâché’s eco-friendly, time-honoured process captivated her. “Vahe is the manifestation of a journey that set foot to reimagine Indian crafts into functional and sculptural art; an ode to the innovations of yesteryear,” she explains. Walekar’s work spans furniture, lighting, and objects that highlight the material’s raw beauty. “My work is guided by a strong belief in the craft process, the craftsperson, and the indigenous materials, yet challenging the functional and aesthetic blocks they are often boxed in.”

Brass and papier-mâché serve as the cornerstones of her work. Her creations embrace brutalism, atypical forms, and tactility. Each piece is a testament to handmade resilience in an age of mass production, reinforcing her belief that traditional crafts must be reimagined for them to survive.

Since its inception, Vahe has garnered global recognition. From Milan Design Week to First Dibs, and accolades like Design Pataki’s Contemporary Craftsmanship Award, the brand continues to carve a distinct identity for itself.

📸: Vahe Ensemble (@vahe.ensemble)

For decades, the depiction of trans characters in Bollywood has been a paradox—it grants visibility while reinforcing harmful stereotypes. 

From ‘Tamanna’ (1997), which gave us one of the first trans characters portrayed with some nuance, to ‘Sangharsh’ (1999), which cast a Hijra character as a child-sacrificing villain, the industry has long struggled with authentic representation on the big screen. 

The 2000s saw trans identities turned into punchlines (‘Masti’ and ‘Kya Kool Hai Hum’), while recent films like ‘Gangubai Kathiawadi’ sidelined them to minor roles. Most recently in 2024, ‘LSD 2’ marked a rare moment of authenticity—featuring a trans actor, Bonita Rajpurohit (@boniiiiiiiiita), playing a trans character.But is this just a one-off, or is Bollywood finally ready to let trans people tell their own stories?

By Jhanvi Adatia (@unshooketh)

#theestablished #transrepresentation

So, will audiences continue to wait or are OTT platforms testing our patience?

LGBTQIA+ philanthropy in India has been piecemeal at best. The Pride Fund is here to change that. Backed by the Keshav Suri Foundation (@keshavsurifoundation), Godrej Industries Group (@godrejdeilab), and Radhika Piramal (@radhikapiramal), the fund will create a ₹2 crore annual corpus for three years—one of the first serious investments in long-term queer rights in India.

The numbers tell a stark story: India receives just 1% of global LGBTQIA+ funding, and only two of the country’s top 50 philanthropists list queer issues as a priority. Meanwhile, eight queer-led organisations—Basera Social Institute, Deepshikha Committee, Vikalp, Sappho for Equality, Karna Subarna Welfare Society, Ya_All, Chhattisgarh Mitwa Sankalp Samiti, and Payana—will be the first recipients of multi-year grants.

The fund will focus on legal aid, livelihood training, crisis intervention workplace inclusion, and awareness program ensuring India’s LGBTQIA+ movements have the resources to thrive. And with the US dismantling USAID, which historically funded global LGBTQIA+ rights, India’s domestic investment in queer futures has never been more urgent.

latestPosts.caption:
Acne isn’t just a skin issue—it’s a mental health struggle that can wreck self-esteem and even fuel anxiety or depression. 

Nearly 86% of individuals with acne report psychological distress, proving it’s linked to more than just one’s appearance. The stigma still lingers, and the emotional toll often outlasts the breakouts. As beauty influencer Prableen Kaur Bhomrah (@prableenkaurbhomrah) puts it, “It wasn’t just about acne; it felt like an attack on my overall appearance and identity.”

A common skin concern, the predicament of acne can go
deeper when it begins to affect one’s mental health. 

Still wondering how? 

Head to the link in bio to read more.

By Ria Bhatia (@riabbhatia)
